article.description: Lauren Jackson scored 27 points and led the Seattle Storm past Sheryl Swoopes and the Houston Comets 71-68 on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Jackson leads Storm with 27 points; Swoopes scores 34
article.linkText: Jackson all action in win over Comets
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- According to Seattle's Lauren Jackson, it's a
good thing Sheryl Swoopes didn't take the last shot for Houston.

"She could have gone like that and it would have gone in,"
Jackson said as she covered her eyes and mimicked throwing a ball
over her shoulder. "She had an unbelievable game."

Despite a career-high 34 points from Swoopes, it was Jackson's
27 that led the Storm past the Comets 71-68 on Tuesday night in a
matchup of potential playoff foes.

The MVP contenders, who entered tied for the WNBA lead at 18
points per game, backed their billing. Swoopes was 15-for-24
shooting topping her previous high of 33, accomplished twice, most
recently on June 18, 2004 against Seattle.

Jackson added nine rebounds and three assists, and got more help
from her supporting cast.

"You had two MVPs on the court. Between Sheryl at one end and
Lauren at the other end, it was fun to watch," Seattle coach Anne
Donovan said. "And Swoopes, anytime you send two people to guard
her as soon as she catches the ball, that tells you how good she
was playing."

Iziane Castro Marques had 11 points, and Sue Bird added 10 for
Seattle. Janell Burse and rookie Tanisha Wright scored eight points
apiece.

Michelle Snow scored 13 points and Janeth Arcain had 11 but no
other Comets player managed more than four. Tina Thompson had just
two points, and newly acquired Dawn Staley went scoreless.

"For whatever reason, we can't put two halves together,"
Swoopes said. "We dug ourselves a hole in the first half and came
back in the second half a completely different team."

Seattle (15-12) is a half-game ahead of Houston (15-13) in the
race for second place and home-court advantage in the playoffs.

Seattle went ahead 60-53 on Jackson's basket with 6:50 left. But
then Swoopes began a highlight-reel of shots.

"I got in a rhythm in the second half and everything seemed
like it was going well," said Swoopes, who scored 25 points in the
second half.

She scored Houston's next nine points -- including driving layups
over Jackson and jumpers over three defenders -- as the Comets
pulled even at 62-62 with 4:14 left.

"You definitely can get caught looking and being a spectator,"
Bird said. "There were just some incredible plays out there."

Seattle built the lead back to 69-64, and went up 71-66 with
47.1 seconds left after Jackson found Simone Edwards open
underneath for a layup.

Swoopes scored with 35 seconds left. Castro Marques missed a
3-pointer with 8.9 seconds left, giving Houston a shot to tie, but
Thompson missed a 3-pointer.

"If we play completely different in the first half, it doesn't
come down to that shot and it's a different outcome," Swoopes
said.

Seattle won its sixth straight at home and improved to 10-3
there.

Houston lost its third straight on the road, and fourth in five
games.

Comets coach Van Chancellor briefly benched all his starters
late in the first half. The five returned to the floor, with less
than two minutes left, and scored the final seven points of the
half to trim a 13-point deficit to six at the break. The early
deficit proved too much to overcome.

"You just cannot drop behind 13 points and beat a team like
this at home," Chancellor said.

Seattle played its second straight game without guard Betty
Lennox, last year's MVP of the finals. Lennox partially tore a
tendon in her left wrist when she fell to the floor driving to the
basket Thursday in Indiana. She also missed Seattle's game in New
York on Saturday.
